  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity almost universally across jurisdictions. It involves the process of making illegally obtained funds (such as proceeds from criminal activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or corruption) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This is done through a series of complex transactions or financial maneuvers.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it facilitates criminal activities, undermines the integrity of financial systems, and enables the continuation of organized crime. Most countries have strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations in place to detect, prevent, and prosecute such activities. International organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) also work to set global standards and promote effective AML measures.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include substantial fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment for individuals and entities involved.",
